Clayton Kershaw
Birthdate: 3/19/1988 (28 y, 23 d)     Bats/Throws: L/L     Height/Weight: 6-4/225     Position: P
Drafted: 2006 June Amateur Draft - Round: 1, Pick: 7, Overall: 7, Team: Los Angeles Dodgers
Contract: $215M / 7 Years (2014 - 2020)
RotoWire News: Kershaw did not factor into the decision in Saturday's 3-2 extra-inning victory over the Giants. He surrendered four hits, two earned runs and a walk over eight innings. He struck out five (4/10/2016)
1/22/2016 - The Worst Clayton Kershaw Pitches of 2015 by August Fagerstrom (FanGraphs) 9
11/11/2015 - Clayton Kershaw Isn't the Clayton Kershaw of Every» by Jeff Sullivan (FanGraphs) 14
11/4/2015 - History, Peaks, and Clayton Kershaw by August Fagerstrom (FanGraphs) 64
10/19/2015 - The Mets Sweep the Cy Young Board (With More to Co» by Shane Tourtellotte (FanGraphs) 22
10/14/2015 - Clayton Kershaw Silences Mets, Narratives by August Fagerstrom (FanGraphs) 48
Profiles:  2010  2011  2012  2013  2014  2015  2016  (Click Year to Expand / Close)
Year in Review: The 21-year-old finished with a .500 record, but Kershaw was dominant in virtually every other category. His fastball averaged nearly 94 mph and trailed only Chris Carpenters with a 1.48 wFB/C. His curveball was even more effective, with a 1.54 wCB/C. And if that was not enough, in June he added a slider to his repertoire. Not merely a different look for hitters, Kershaws slider is another outstanding offering, with a 1.36 wSL/C. By the end of the season, Kershaw was throwing his slider (16%) more often than his curve (11%). It all gave him plenty of weapons to attack hitters, and resulted in a 9.64 K/9, the sixth-best mark in the Majors among starters. After being an extreme ground-ball pitcher in 2008 (1.54 GB/FB), Kershaw allowed more flies than grounders last year. But he tied Carpenter for the fewest homers allowed (seven) among qualified starters.

The Year Ahead: Due in part to his 4.79 BB/9 rate, Kershaws FIP (3.08) was higher than his ERA (2.79) last year. Add in that he had a 77.4 LOB% and his HR/FB rate was an unsustainable 4.1% and Kershaw will likely see his ERA rise. But there are so many variables to consider, it makes projecting him a difficult task. Is he a ground-ball or fly-ball pitcher? Can he continue to throw nasty pitches with both a curve and slider? Will Kershaw approach the 2.79 BB/9 rate he had at Double-A in 2008? But while his ERA may be up in the air, it is likely that Kershaw will top last years victory total. The other nine starters in 2009 to top 9.0 K/9 averaged 14.6 W last year. The Dodgers club was very careful with Kershaws work load, as he threw 171 innings in 31 starts. Even with a minimal increase in innings pitched, Kershaw should approach 200 strikeouts next year. (Brian Joura)
Profile: Kershaw has great stuff and has been a highly thought of prospect since his days in high school, so after posting a 2.91 ERA as a 22-year-old, its easy to buy into the narrative that he is one of the games elite pitchers. I wouldnt make that leap just yet a bulk of Kershaws run prevention were built on the twin towers of unsustainability HR/FB rate (just 5.8%) and BABIP (.275). While Kershaw may prove to be able to beat the league average in both of the marks, smart money will bet on significant regression in both areas in 2011, and without a drastic improvement in his command, his ERA will almost certainly go up this year. Consistency in strike throwing is still a problem as well, and high pitch counts have led to shortened outings and fewer opportunities for wins. While he has all the potential to become an ace, he isnt there yet, and if prices reflect a belief that he arrived as a #1 starter in 2010, your money is better spent elsewhere. (Dave Cameron)

The Quick Opinion: A very good pitcher who might be unfairly perceived as a great one already. Could get there, but don't pay for the assumption he already did.
Profile: It all came together for the 23-year-old last season. Kershaw's walk rate dropped to 2.08, yet he maintained his excellent 9.58 strikeout rate. He's also becoming one of the most dependable starters in baseball, making 30+ starts and increasing his workload over the past three seasons. In a previous life, Kershaw's curveball was referred to as "public enemy number one, " but his slider was his best weapon last season. It will be tough for Kershaw to improve on his 2.28 ERA, but his 2.47 FIP suggests that he's capable of similar success in the future. As long as he stays healthy, he'll be one of the best pitchers in fantasy baseball next season. (Chris Cwik)

The Quick Opinion: Armed with the best slider in baseball, Kershaw absolutely dominated the competition last season. He's still just 24 -- and while it will be tough to improve any more -- he should be one of the best starters in baseball for the foreseeable future.
Profile: Kershaw's 2012 was pretty darn close to his 2011, and if not for a spectacular season (and story) from R.A. Dickey, Kershaw might have repeated as the NL's Cy Young award winner. Kershaw did slip a little in 2012. His strikeout rate dropped from 9.57 to 9.05 and his walk rate rose to 2.49 from 2.08. But his K/9 was still the fifth-highest in the National League. His BB/9 was only good for 23rd-best, and contributed to a 1.02 WHIP, compared to 0.98 in 2011. But Kershaw continued to excel at the things that make him an elite pitcher. He induced swinging strikes on 11% of his pitches and held hitters to a .204 batting average. Only Gio Gonzalez had a lower BAA in the National League. Kershaw's kept his batting average on balls in play at or below .275 for the fourth consecutive season, which suggests Kershaw's pitches induce more weakly-hit balls. That's especially true in 2012, when the Dodgers' defense rated only 8th-best in the National League. If Kershaw stays healthy -- not a given, considering his hip issues in the past -- expect another monster season from the lanky left-hander in 2013. (Wendy Thurm/@hangingsliders)

The Quick Opinion: Kershaw was at the top of his game again in 2012. The lefty nearly matched his remarkable Cy Young award-winning season from 2011, but a growing walk rate and shrinking strikeout rate made him only one of the five best pitchers in the National League, instead of the best. He misses bats on more than 10% of his pitches, and induces weak contact when hitters do connect. Look for Kershaw to dominate the National League again in 2013.
Profile: Never draft a pitcher in the first round, unless his last name is Kershaw. He is the ultimate fantasy pitcher in that both his health and his skills are incredibly stable and he excels across the board statistically. The only variance in his game is his win total, proving he is at least human and not immune to issues other pitchers have to deal with. Over the past five seasons, his strikeout rate has been at least 25% and over the last three seasons, he has put the struggles with control behind him.Combine the low walk totals with the very low home run totals and low hit rates, and you have the perfect formula for fantastic ratios. The surprising thing is that he is getting even better. His swing and miss rate has improved each of the past five seasons, and that hammer of God curve he throws has kept his chase rate over 30% each of the past three seasons. He is a perfect example of pitcher establishing their own batting average on balls in play baseline as his 5-year average is .270; he scoffs at your .290-.310 range. There is no reason to expect anything different in 2014. (Jason Collette)

The Quick Opinion: The old adage goes that you should never, ever, draft a pitcher in the 1st round. Rules are made to be broken, and you should do so with Kershaw in 2014.
Profile: Theres not much that has to be said about Clayton Kershaw. Hes the best pitcher in the league and it carries over to fantasy baseball as well. Unless you are in a NL-only league, no matter what category or league settings you have, Kershaw is the top dog. Kershaw led the league in wins, ERA (for the fourth consecutive year), WHIP and complete games. Kershaws 239 strikeouts only placed him seventh in the league but thats because he missed his first few starts of the year with a strained muscle in his back. That injury clearly didnt affect his 2014 season and besides the fact he throws baseballs for a living, Kershaw isnt a particularly large injury risk. It would surprise nobody if Kershaw leads the league, or is close to it, in all fantasy baseball categories and that places him firmly number one on all draft boards among starting pitchers. A few years ago, the idea of any starting pitcher having an ERA under 2 sounded insane, Kershaw could do it for the third year in a row. Wow. (Ben Pasinkoff)

The Quick Opinion: The best pitcher in major league baseball.
Profile: He failed to earn a third straight Cy Young award, but that does not mean that Kershaw is no longer the best pitcher in baseball (or the world?). His accolades this season read like a laundry list, as he led all qualified Major League starters in SIERA, FIP, xFIP and wins above replacement by hefty margins, while also leading strikeout rate, strikeout minus walk rate, swinging strike rate, and strikeouts. That he allowed an uncharacteristic 10% home run per fly ball rate, his highest since his 2008 debut, may have cost him the trophy. But who cares? His strikeout rate has now remained above 30% for two straight seasons, and his control, which at one time was his bugaboo, is now elite. He has even pushed his ground ball rate up to the 50% range. This man is definitely a robot sent from the future to make a mockery of this wonderful game we call baseball. (Mike Podhorzer)

The Quick Opinion: Still the best pitcher in all the land, regardless of what the Cy Young voters have to say about it. The only starting pitcher that should require no hesitation to draft in the first round.
